00:01:39.070 --> 00:01:42.150
So last day we looked at
binary phase diagrams.

00:01:42.150 --> 00:01:44.560
And we looked at two
different types of

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:45.910
binary phase diagrams.

00:01:45.910 --> 00:01:49.190
Type one, which is the
lenticular, and type two,

00:01:49.190 --> 00:01:53.100
which is synclinal, and in both
instances, we came upon

00:01:53.100 --> 00:01:57.410
two-phase regimes, and when p
equals 2, that causes you to

00:01:57.410 --> 00:02:01.200
start thinking along the lines
of phase separation.

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:04.840
Phase separation then
invokes a tie line.

00:02:04.840 --> 00:02:07.910
The tie line tells you the
composition of the two phases

00:02:07.910 --> 00:02:10.920
present, and the lever rule
tells you the relative

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:13.510
quantities, the relative
amounts, of

00:02:13.510 --> 00:02:15.740
the two phases present.

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:19.290
What I want to do today is talk
about the last type of

00:02:19.290 --> 00:02:23.290
phase diagram that we'll speak
about in 3091, and that's

00:02:23.290 --> 00:02:25.220
called type three.

00:02:25.220 --> 00:02:27.000
I came up with these
very original,

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:28.860
easy to remember labels.

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:29.600
So type three.

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:34.870
What characterizes type
three phase diagrams?

00:02:34.870 --> 00:02:43.980
Well, we have partial solubility
of A and B. We're

00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:44.700
doing all of this.

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:47.950
A is one of the components, and
B is the other component.

00:02:47.950 --> 00:02:51.600
So partial solubility of A and
B, and change of state.

00:02:55.550 --> 00:03:02.730
And the result of this set of
characteristics is freezing

00:03:02.730 --> 00:03:04.510
point depression of
both components.

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:20.570
And that's different from the
situation in type one.

00:03:20.570 --> 00:03:27.950
In type one, you see, if we
have B on the right, then

00:03:27.950 --> 00:03:31.980
adding at A to B, if this is
pure B over here, and this is

00:03:31.980 --> 00:03:36.270
pure A over here, adding A
to B causes the freezing

00:03:36.270 --> 00:03:37.510
point of B to fall.

00:03:37.510 --> 00:03:41.790
But adding B to A causes the
freezing point of A to rise.

00:03:41.790 --> 00:03:44.870
In this type three, we're going
to have freezing point

00:03:44.870 --> 00:03:49.820
depression of both B and A.
That's the difference between

00:03:49.820 --> 00:03:52.780
the type one and type three.

00:03:52.780 --> 00:03:55.970
And actually, I'm going
to approach this by a

00:03:55.970 --> 00:03:58.230
hybridization of sorts.

00:03:58.230 --> 00:04:02.260
So I'm going to consider
type three a hybrid.

00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:08.910
It's a hybrid diagram of the
lens and the syncline.

00:04:08.910 --> 00:04:14.400
I'm going to blend the lens and
the syncline, and show you

00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:16.250
how to do that.

00:04:16.250 --> 00:04:19.470
So let me get one of those
up here, so that

00:04:19.470 --> 00:04:21.970
we can look at it.

00:04:21.970 --> 00:04:23.990
So what I'm going to do
here, this is a great

00:04:23.990 --> 00:04:24.990
diagram to look at.

00:04:24.990 --> 00:04:26.110
It's gold nickel.

00:04:26.110 --> 00:04:29.340
And at the top, we have a type
one, and at the bottom, we

00:04:29.340 --> 00:04:30.220
have a type two.

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:32.460
And what I'm going to do, is
I'm going to mix them.

00:04:32.460 --> 00:04:33.690
I'm going to hybridize them.

00:04:33.690 --> 00:04:35.710
I'm going to bring this
bottom one up and have

00:04:35.710 --> 00:04:38.650
it touch the lens.

00:04:38.650 --> 00:04:41.886
And so we get is something
that looks like this.

00:04:41.886 --> 00:04:46.690
We'll plot temperature
versus composition.

00:04:46.690 --> 00:04:47.450
Left--

00:04:47.450 --> 00:04:48.960
so here's temperature.

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:50.140
Composition.

00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:54.450
On the left I have pure A and
on the right I have pure B.

00:04:54.450 --> 00:05:00.540
And we'll start here with the
melting point of pure B. And

00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:05.400
when I add A to B, I'm going to
get the depression that we

00:05:05.400 --> 00:05:07.420
see in the type one diagram.

00:05:07.420 --> 00:05:11.820
We want to start off like this,
and use everything we've

00:05:11.820 --> 00:05:12.910
learned up until now.

00:05:12.910 --> 00:05:15.640
So up here, we have
all liquid.

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:17.430
This is all liquid.

00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:20.770
And over here, this is
a solid solution.

00:05:20.770 --> 00:05:23.560
This is pure B, and this
is B that has a

00:05:23.560 --> 00:05:24.980
little bit of A in it.

00:05:24.980 --> 00:05:27.190
So we're going to use the old
metallurgical definition and

00:05:27.190 --> 00:05:28.570
call this beta.

00:05:28.570 --> 00:05:34.940
Beta meaning, beta is a solution
of A and B, but it's

00:05:34.940 --> 00:05:37.980
very rich in B. It's almost pure
B. So I'm going to call

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:46.700
this a B-rich solid solution
of A and B.

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:50.490
And we know from last day, you
can't go from p equals 1,

00:05:50.490 --> 00:05:53.380
let's get those labels up here,
you can't go from p

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:56.870
equals 1 to another p equals
1 without going

00:05:56.870 --> 00:05:58.080
through a p equals 2.

00:05:58.080 --> 00:06:02.610
So this is single phase and this
is single phase, and that

00:06:02.610 --> 00:06:06.410
means this one here must
be two phrase.

00:06:06.410 --> 00:06:07.730
And what are the two phases?

00:06:07.730 --> 00:06:10.490
The two phases are the phases
that are on either side.

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:13.630
So this must be liquid
plus beta in here.

00:06:13.630 --> 00:06:15.400
And that means--

00:06:15.400 --> 00:06:21.610
phase rule-- p equals 2,
tie line, lever rule.

00:06:21.610 --> 00:06:24.000
So that's what's going
on in there.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:27.020
And then the difference is,
on this side, if this is t

00:06:27.020 --> 00:06:31.140
melting point of A we're going
to start off with the same

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:32.380
concept here.

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:35.090
That we're going to get freezing
point depression of

00:06:35.090 --> 00:06:36.620
A, as well.

00:06:36.620 --> 00:06:38.500
So we'll have the liquid.

00:06:38.500 --> 00:06:41.580
Over here we'll have
an A-rich solution.

00:06:41.580 --> 00:06:43.300
So then I'm going to
call that alpha.

00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:51.140
So alpha is an A-rich solid
solution of A and B. And then

00:06:51.140 --> 00:06:53.080
that must mean that in
between here, we

00:06:53.080 --> 00:06:56.460
have liquid plus alpha.

00:06:56.460 --> 00:06:57.865
And these keep going.

00:06:57.865 --> 00:07:00.640
And in addition, down at the
low end, I'm going to start

00:07:00.640 --> 00:07:03.480
with a syncline.

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:06.220
I'm going to start with a
syncline, coming up like so,

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:07.650
and coming up like so.

00:07:07.650 --> 00:07:10.550
See what I'm doing?

00:07:10.550 --> 00:07:13.610
I'm taking the lens.

00:07:13.610 --> 00:07:15.260
I'm going to meet
the syncline.

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:15.990
So what's here?

00:07:15.990 --> 00:07:18.160
This is alpha, this is beta.

00:07:18.160 --> 00:07:20.660
What's inside the syncline?

00:07:20.660 --> 00:07:24.780
This is miscibility gap, so
this is alpha plus beta.

00:07:24.780 --> 00:07:26.860
So let's keep the phase
labeling here.

00:07:26.860 --> 00:07:28.910
This is p equals 2.

00:07:28.910 --> 00:07:33.850
And look at how things have
worked out so nicely.

00:07:33.850 --> 00:07:40.040
p equals 1, p equals 2, p equals
1, p equals 2, p equals

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:42.240
1, p equals 2.

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:42.895
So nice.

00:07:42.895 --> 00:07:45.420
And what happens when
all this intersects?

00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:47.790
It intersects like so.

00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:50.790
Try to do this, stretch
it a little bit.

00:07:50.790 --> 00:07:54.390
So these two lines connect.

00:07:54.390 --> 00:07:56.370
They cross at this point.

00:07:56.370 --> 00:07:58.000
They touch at this point,
the don't cross.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:07:59.100
They just touch.

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:04.430
And then this arc comes up like
so, this comes down like

00:08:04.430 --> 00:08:09.923
so, and now we have a line
across here, and this comes

00:08:09.923 --> 00:08:11.400
down like so.

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:11.820
OK?

00:08:11.820 --> 00:08:18.970
So the syncline stops at this
value, which is the minimum

00:08:18.970 --> 00:08:22.330
temperature dictated by
the two liquidus.

00:08:22.330 --> 00:08:24.900
We have a liquidus here and a
liquidus here, and this gets

00:08:24.900 --> 00:08:27.060
you down to the lowest
temperature.

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:32.090
And let's look at the phase mix
going in this direction.

00:08:32.090 --> 00:08:38.430
p equals 1, p equals 2, p
equals 1, p equals 2.

00:08:38.430 --> 00:08:40.730
What's happening at
this point here?

00:08:40.730 --> 00:08:43.320
This point, we have three
phases in equilibrium.

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:45.910
We have liquid, alpha,
and beta.

00:08:45.910 --> 00:08:47.510
And this is the special
point here.

00:08:47.510 --> 00:08:49.080
This is called the eutectic.

00:08:49.080 --> 00:08:54.080
This is the eutectic, which is
the temperature at which we

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:57.480
get liquid, all liquid,
at the lowest value.

00:08:57.480 --> 00:09:00.570
So I'm going to call this here,
I'm going to call this

00:09:00.570 --> 00:09:04.020
point e, and e is
the eutectic.

00:09:09.380 --> 00:09:13.610
Lowest melting point
on the diagram.

00:09:13.610 --> 00:09:17.480
Comes from the Greek, meaning
easy melting.

00:09:17.480 --> 00:09:20.120
And at the eutectic, eutectic
is special.

00:09:20.120 --> 00:09:24.170
Here we have p equals 3.

00:09:24.170 --> 00:09:26.040
It's a triple point.

00:09:26.040 --> 00:09:28.290
The eutectic is a
triple point.

00:09:28.290 --> 00:09:29.740
OK.

00:09:29.740 --> 00:09:33.550
So now let's take a look
at some of the

00:09:33.550 --> 00:09:35.830
examples of such diagrams.

00:09:35.830 --> 00:09:37.320
All right?

00:09:37.320 --> 00:09:40.510
This is a good one now that
winter is upon us.

00:09:40.510 --> 00:09:43.640
This is the antifreeze
diagram.

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:45.970
So on the left, I have pure
water, and on the right, I

00:09:45.970 --> 00:09:47.840
have pure ethylene glycol.

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:50.550
And as you can see, if you add
glycol to water, you get

00:09:50.550 --> 00:09:52.010
freezing point depression.

00:09:52.010 --> 00:09:54.430
If you add water to glycol,
you get freezing point

00:09:54.430 --> 00:09:57.990
depression with a eutectic here
at roughly two-thirds.

00:09:57.990 --> 00:10:00.480
This is in volume percent,
because that's practical unit.

00:10:00.480 --> 00:10:03.300
When you mix glycol with water,
you do so by volume,

00:10:03.300 --> 00:10:06.830
not by mass, or certainly
not by moles.

00:10:06.830 --> 00:10:12.310
So if you mix two glycol with
one part water, you'll end up

00:10:12.310 --> 00:10:16.040
with a eutectic of minus 69
degrees C, or minus 92

00:10:16.040 --> 00:10:17.050
Fahrenheit.

00:10:17.050 --> 00:10:19.250
So that ought to take care
of your driving needs.

00:10:19.250 --> 00:10:20.260
All right?

00:10:20.260 --> 00:10:24.230
Now practically speaking, we
put an equal volume mix.

00:10:24.230 --> 00:10:27.110
So it's about a 50-50
glycol-water mix.

00:10:27.110 --> 00:10:31.420
And that gives you liquidus
depression down to about not

00:10:31.420 --> 00:10:32.370
quite minus 40.

00:10:32.370 --> 00:10:35.940
It's about minus 35 Fahrenheit,
which ought to

00:10:35.940 --> 00:10:37.630
take care of most peoples'
driving needs.

00:10:37.630 --> 00:10:41.340
Remember, what we're trying to
do is to prevent the liquid in

00:10:41.340 --> 00:10:43.280
the engine block
from freezing.

00:10:43.280 --> 00:10:47.860
because if it does freeze, you
know that ice has a larger

00:10:47.860 --> 00:10:51.950
volume than water, and that
energy is so great that you'll

00:10:51.950 --> 00:10:53.880
crack the engine block.

00:10:53.880 --> 00:10:56.100
So you have to prevent it from
freezing, the water from

00:10:56.100 --> 00:10:58.160
freezing, and so you
add the glycol.

00:10:58.160 --> 00:11:00.730
If, by chance, the temperature
dropped to minus 50, you'd

00:11:00.730 --> 00:11:02.550
still be OK, because you'd
be in the slush

00:11:02.550 --> 00:11:04.240
zone, two-phase regime.

00:11:04.240 --> 00:11:06.610
You'd have some water
ice forming, but

00:11:06.610 --> 00:11:08.010
you'd still have slush.

00:11:08.010 --> 00:11:10.370
And by the way, why does this
not look like this?

00:11:10.370 --> 00:11:16.450
It turns out that the amount of
solid solution behavior of

00:11:16.450 --> 00:11:19.020
a glycol in water is
vanishingly small.

00:11:19.020 --> 00:11:20.990
So this point is slammed
up over here.

00:11:20.990 --> 00:11:24.790
So that's why you don't see the
right side of the lens.

00:11:24.790 --> 00:11:27.950
And likewise, on the other
side, the amount of water

00:11:27.950 --> 00:11:30.870
that's soluble in glycol
is vanishingly small.

00:11:30.870 --> 00:11:35.350
So according to this scale, you
don't see the beta or the

00:11:35.350 --> 00:11:36.530
alpha phases here.

00:11:36.530 --> 00:11:40.100
It looks like it's pure, but
it can't be, because of the

00:11:40.100 --> 00:11:43.290
phase rule here.

00:11:43.290 --> 00:11:47.490
Now, you might say, well, why
don't we run pure glycol?

00:11:47.490 --> 00:11:49.700
Because somebody might say,
I'll just run pure glycol.

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:52.020
Well, here's the problem with
running pure glycol.

00:11:52.020 --> 00:11:55.710
First of all, if you get beyond
two-thirds, the melting

00:11:55.710 --> 00:11:56.980
point rises.

00:11:56.980 --> 00:12:00.740
But then you could say, well,
but pure glycol, the solid

00:12:00.740 --> 00:12:04.220
glycol, has a smaller volume
than liquid glycol, so it

00:12:04.220 --> 00:12:06.730
wouldn't freeze and crack
the engine block.

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:09.910
But there's another problem
here, and that is that the

00:12:09.910 --> 00:12:14.500
viscosity of water is 1 in these
units, centipoise, and

00:12:14.500 --> 00:12:15.950
glycol is 21.

00:12:15.950 --> 00:12:18.050
So you'd probably burn out your
water pump by running

00:12:18.050 --> 00:12:20.230
pure glycol, because it's so
viscous, the water pump is

00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:22.480
going to be fatigued
by running.

00:12:22.480 --> 00:12:23.530
And here's the point.

00:12:23.530 --> 00:12:31.330
This is the 50-50, minus
37 degrees Celsius.

00:12:31.330 --> 00:12:32.080
OK.

00:12:32.080 --> 00:12:35.940
And so what I've done, is I've
superimposed the solid-liquid

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:37.870
diagrams with the liquid
vapor diagram.

00:12:37.870 --> 00:12:40.190
And this is one of the times
when nature is kind.

00:12:40.190 --> 00:12:43.220
So when you add glycol to water,
water is on the left

00:12:43.220 --> 00:12:46.590
here, as you add glycol to
water, you get freezing point

00:12:46.590 --> 00:12:50.010
depression, and you get boiling
point elevation.

00:12:50.010 --> 00:12:54.470
So adding glycol to water opens
up the liquid range.

00:12:54.470 --> 00:12:57.810
You want to stave off boiling,
because boiling will cause

00:12:57.810 --> 00:13:00.760
lousy cooling, and the engine
will overheat, and you want to

00:13:00.760 --> 00:13:03.730
stave off freezing, which will
cause the ice to form and

00:13:03.730 --> 00:13:05.720
crack the engine block,
and you get both.

00:13:05.720 --> 00:13:08.250
Then you put the pressure cap,
and then jump this up to about

00:13:08.250 --> 00:13:10.530
265 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:13:10.530 --> 00:13:13.370
So this is a very good example
of management of the

00:13:13.370 --> 00:13:17.040
properties of the coolant
through chemical change.

00:13:17.040 --> 00:13:19.810
And the binary phase diagram
eutectic type is a critical

00:13:19.810 --> 00:13:21.580
piece here.

00:13:21.580 --> 00:13:24.410
Again, apropos of the weather,
if you get ice on the

00:13:24.410 --> 00:13:27.210
sidewalks, if this rain freezes,
it's terrible here.

00:13:27.210 --> 00:13:30.110
Those of you who are in the
Northeast for the first time,

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:30.930
this is bad.

00:13:30.930 --> 00:13:33.910
Not with what you see now, but
when this freezes, it's a

00:13:33.910 --> 00:13:35.580
skating rink, and you
can't see it.

