00:20:43.960 --> 00:20:47.480
Plus the wavelength of copper
K-alpha radiation.

00:20:47.480 --> 00:20:50.112
1.5418 angstroms.

00:20:50.112 --> 00:20:51.380
Yeah.

00:20:51.380 --> 00:20:52.890
So what's the magic here?

00:20:52.890 --> 00:20:57.400
The magic here is, the solder
must be low-melting enough

00:20:57.400 --> 00:20:59.560
that when you're-- remember,
you've got your

00:20:59.560 --> 00:21:00.720
microelectronic device.

00:21:00.720 --> 00:21:03.090
You've already got your chip,
and you're putting wires.

00:21:03.090 --> 00:21:06.170
You want to put enough heat in
to solder the wires, but you

00:21:06.170 --> 00:21:08.790
don't want to have to raise the
temperature so much that

00:21:08.790 --> 00:21:11.020
you can damage the rest
of the device.

00:21:11.020 --> 00:21:12.280
So you say, well, why don't
you get something

00:21:12.280 --> 00:21:13.650
that's lower melting?

00:21:13.650 --> 00:21:16.390
Well, if it's lower melting,
you know from running your

00:21:16.390 --> 00:21:19.290
laptops and charging your cell
phones, they get warm.

00:21:19.290 --> 00:21:20.900
So it's a Goldilocks problem.

00:21:20.900 --> 00:21:23.620
If the melting point of the
solder is too low, you might

00:21:23.620 --> 00:21:25.910
encounter that temperature
in service, and

00:21:25.910 --> 00:21:27.460
pop all of the joints.

00:21:27.460 --> 00:21:30.040
If the melting point of the
solder is too high, then you

00:21:30.040 --> 00:21:33.730
have to use so much energy to
make the joints that you

00:21:33.730 --> 00:21:36.580
damage some of the
microelectronic componentry.

00:21:36.580 --> 00:21:40.190
So this has to be in the right
temperature range.

00:21:40.190 --> 00:21:42.930
The problem with this excellent,
excellent solder is

00:21:42.930 --> 00:21:44.660
that it contains lead.

00:21:44.660 --> 00:21:47.590
No one's going to get lead
poisoning from using a device.

00:21:47.590 --> 00:21:51.160
But the disposal of the device
ends up introducing the lead

00:21:51.160 --> 00:21:54.200
into the landfill, and then
if it soaks in an aqueous

00:21:54.200 --> 00:21:56.030
solution, you could get
leeching, et cetera.

00:21:56.030 --> 00:21:59.570
So there's a lot of research
right now on trying to find

00:21:59.570 --> 00:22:01.680
